The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, January 14, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Several long-distance trains arrived hours late at Howrah and Sealdah stations on Tuesday because of dense fog in the northern part of the country. Eastern Railway officials said New Delhi-Howrah Rajdhani Express arrived 10 hours late at Howrah. Poorva Express (six hours), Doon Express (eight hours), Amritsar Mail (14 hours), Kalka Mail (4 hours 30 minutes), Shipra Express (six hours) and Mumbai Mail via Allahabad (three hours) too arrived behind schedule at Howrah station. New Delhi-Sealdah Rajdhani Express (6 hours 30 minutes) and Jammu Tawi Express (nine hours) arrived late at Sealdah station.																																																		Amar Mallick and Ram Swaroop Mallick, arrested for dacoity in Short Street in March 1997, were sentenced to seven years of rigorous imprisonment by the second Fast Track court on Tuesday. The two convicts, allegedly along with three others, Sheikh Munna, Mir Anwar and Muharram Gazia, looted Rs 35,000, electronic gadgets and gold ornaments from 8 Short Street. The judge also asked them to pay a fine of Rs 5,000 each, failing which they would have to serve another six months in jail. The three others were acquitted.																																																		Calcutta Municipal Corporation will demolish unauthorised shops in Posta in the Burrabazar area. This was announced by mayor-in-council Rajib Deb on Tuesday after visiting the area along with deputy mayor Meena Devi Purohit. The officials visited the area to inspect the condition of the garbage vats. 																																																		 Police arrested 50 criminals, including Mithun Upadhyay, a gangster in Habra on the northern fringes of the city. District superintendent of police Basudeb Bag said the arrests were made after a night-long raid. Mithun was picked up from near Chaitanya College. He is wanted in a number of cases, including snatching and dacoity. A huge cache of firearms was found in his possession.																																																		A 25-year-old contract labourer, Halim Seikh, was killed when a portion of a building collapsed at Prafulla Kanan in Baguiati on the northern fringes of the city on Tuesday. Police said Halim was working for a promoter with other labourers to demolish a century-old building. Police could neither trace the owners of the building nor the promoter.																																																		 The Book Fair, from January 28 to February 8, will have an information technology pavilion with 31 stalls. Tickets for the fair will be available from Metro stations like every year. In addition, there will be a big pavilion measuring about 3,000 sq ft, specifically marked for childrens books.																																																		 The timings of Howrah-Adra-Chakradharpur Passenger will be revised from January 15. South Eastern Railway officials said timings of the train on the Howrah-Kharagpur-Metyal Sahar route would remain unchanged. With the revised timings, 315 Howrah-Adra-Chakradharpur Passenger leaving Howrah will reach Adra and Chakradharpur at 5.35 am and 10.45 am respectively. Subsequently, the timings of 315A Howrah-Adra-Bokaro Passenger, 476 Bhojudih-Adra Passenger, 477 Up Adra-Purulia Passenger and 478 Down Purulia-Adra Passenger would also be revised, SER officials said.																																																		Swami Vivekananda: the life, works and research, a CD, is available at MusicWorld for Rs 300 till the end of this week. Being offered in association with Ramakrishna Mission, Advaita Ashrama, the compilation includes complete works of the Swami, a biographical account and rare photographs.																																																		Gopal Biswas, 26, the newspaper hawker who was hit by a minibus near Ranikuthi on Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose on Sunday, died at Nilratan Sircar Medical College and Hospital on Tuesday. TO Calcutta Metropolitan Ladies  circle 65 for distributing 40 blankets among street-dwellers
